Understanding Randomess & Chance with Numpy

Author

Russ Zaliznyak

Published

October 24, 2024

Introduction

Imagine your website converts 10% of its visitors to paying customers. Over the course of 10,000 visitors, how many converts should we expect? A quick back of the envelope calculation shows we should expect 1,000 conversions: \[ 10000 \, \text{visitors} * \frac{10 \, \text{conversions}}{100 \, \text{visitors}} = 1000 \, \text{conversions} \]

But how much could that number vary each time we run this experiment?

Simulating Data

Letâ€™s simulate the process of website conversion 1,000,000x with n = 10,000 and p = 0.10 (conversion rate).

import timeit
from numpy.random import binomial, seed
seed(10)

conversion_rate = 0.10
number_of_visitors = int(1e4)
standard_error = (conversion_rate*(1-conversion_rate)/number_of_visitors)**0.5


start = timeit.default_timer()
number_simulated_experiments = int(1e6)
control_simulated_results = binomial(
    number_of_visitors, conversion_rate, size=number_simulated_experiments
)
stop = timeit.default_timer()
print(f"simulation runtime: {round(stop-start,3)} secs")
simulation runtime: 0.03 secs

Examining Results

At the end of each simulation, we record and plot how many conversions took place. Each panel represents the results of plotting more simulations together.

Our first simulation only generated 965 conversions. But with enough simulations plotted together, are you seeing a pattern develop?

Code 
import plotly.subplots as sp
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px
from math import ceil
from numpy import where, linspace, min, max, cumsum, percentile, array, mean


df = pd.DataFrame(control_simulated_results, columns=["value"])
running_total_df = df.copy()

# Count occurrences and create a running total
running_total_df["count"] = running_total_df["value"].map(
    running_total_df["value"].value_counts()
)
running_total_df["running_total"] = running_total_df.groupby("value").cumcount() + 1

# Rearranging to match the running total of occurrences
running_total_df = running_total_df[["value", "count", "running_total"]]



number_experiments_list = [
    1,
    50,
    200,
    400,
    800,
    2500,
    int(1e4),
    int(1e5),
]
subplot_titles = tuple([f"# sims = {value}" for value in number_experiments_list])
number_experiments_list_length = len(number_experiments_list)


number_cols = 4
number_rows = ceil(number_experiments_list_length / number_cols)
BLUE = "#82b2e0"
RED = "#bd0707"
fig = sp.make_subplots(
    rows=number_rows,
    cols=number_cols,
    subplot_titles=subplot_titles,
    vertical_spacing=0.1,
)

for j in range(len(number_experiments_list)):
    number = number_experiments_list[j]
    fig_0 = px.scatter(
        running_total_df[0:number],
        x="value",
        y="running_total",
        color_discrete_sequence = [BLUE]
    )

    row = 1 + int(j / number_cols)
    col = 1 + j - (row - 1) * number_cols
    fig.add_trace(fig_0.data[0], row=row, col=col)


fig.update_layout(height=600)
x_ticks = [950, 1000, 1050]
for j in range(len(number_experiments_list)):
    row = 1 + int(j / number_cols)
    col = 1 + j - (row - 1) * number_cols

    fig.update_xaxes(
        tickvals=x_ticks if j > 0 else [int(df["value"].iloc[0])], row=row, col=col
    )

fig.show()

Use Simulation Results to Estimate Randomness

  1. Whatâ€™s the chance of 950 conversions or fewer?
  2. Whatâ€™s the chance of 1050 conversions or more?
  3. Whatâ€™s the chance of between 950 and 1050 conversions (exclusive)?

Verify Results

Rate-based metrics are normally distributed; so we use the normal approximation to confirm our results with mean 0.1 and standard_error = 0.003.

\[ F(0.095) = \Phi\left( \frac{0.095 - 0.10}{0.003} \right) = \Phi\left( -1.67 \right) = 0.0478 \]

                               Type Probability
0           950 conversions or less       4.78%
1          1050 conversions or more       4.78%
2  Between 950 and 1050 conversions      90.44%

Differences are explained by the continuous nature of the normal approximation. Our data is discrete.

Conclusion

This simple example shows numpy.random can be used to simulate data. You can use it to build intuition for AB testing and other analysis.

Upcoming papers will show how to extend numpy.random to model sequential testing, Bayesian testing, and other complex processes. Simulation studies help us understand our problems when closed-form analytical solutions may not be readily available.
